ederal authority. Instead, Schapiro proposes a polyphonic model that emphasizes the valuable interaction of state and federal law, one that more accurately describes the intersecting realities of local and national power. Through an analysis of several legal and policy debates, Polyphonic Federalism demonstrates how a multifaceted government can best realize the potential of federalism to protect fundamental rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCivil rightsxUnited States. 0aCivil rightszUnited States. 0aFederal governmentxUnited States. 0aFederal governmentzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  afederalism, government, power, democracy, liberty, freedom, authority, policy, civil rights, nationalism, law, courts, adjudication, nonfiction, politics, political science, constitution, governance, supreme court, judges, legislation, state, local, national, federal, history, administration, full faith and credit, congress, legal system.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022673662440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226736648423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226736648/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles